titanic_set <- read_csv("data/titanic_decision_tree_data.csv")

shuffle_index <- sample(1:nrow(titanic_set))

# shuffle the data so class order isn't in order - need this for training/testing split later on 
titanic_set <- titanic_set[shuffle_index, ]

1.1 Question 1

#Take only observations which have a survived flag (i.e. that aren’t missing)
titanic_set <- titanic_set %>% 
  filter(!is.na(survived))

#Turn your important variables into factors (sex, survived, pclass, embarkation)

titanic_set <- titanic_set %>% 
mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)


#Create an age_status variable which groups individuals under (and including) 16 years of age into a category called “child” category and those over 16 into a category called “adult”.

titanic_set <- titanic_set %>% 
  mutate(age_status = if_else(age <= 16, "child", "adult" )) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(age_status))



#Drop any variables you don’t need (X1, passenger_id, name, ticket, far, cabin)
titanic_set <-  titanic_set %>% 
select(-c(X1, passenger_id, name, ticket, fare, cabin))


#also set age_status to factor
titanic_set <-  titanic_set %>% 
  mutate(age_status = as_factor(age_status))
view(titanic_set)

titanic_set <- titanic_set %>% 
  mutate(survived = if_else(survived == 1, "lived", "died" ))

view(titanic_set)

# create a test sample index thast is 20% of the total sample (142)
test_index <- sample(1:n_data, size = n_data*0.2)

# create test set of 142 rows
titantic_set_test  <- slice(titanic_set, test_index)


# create training set of the remaining data (include all but the test_set)

  1. Write down what this tells you, in detail. What variables are important? What does each node tell you? Who has the highest chance of surviving? Who has the lowest? Provide as much detail as you can.

#ANS The above decision tree tels us that the following variables are important: sex, pclass, age and sib_sp The top line tells us that the probability of death is 0.41. The 2nd line tells us that if you are male the probability you died is 0.21, th eprobaility for females surviving is 0.75 The 3rd line tells you that for males with an age of 6.5 or more, the probability they died was 0.18. It also states that for females, if your pclass was not 3 (i.e. 1 or 2) the probability you lived was 0.94 The 4th line tells us that for males under 6.5 years of age, those with less than 3 siblings had a probability of 0.11 that they would die. Those that had 3 or more siblings were expected to live (probability of 1) For females it tells that with those with a pclass of 3, if they were 39 years or older, the probability they died was 0.08. Line 5 tells us that for those younger than 39, the probability they lived was 0.51, for those women, if they has 3 or more siblings the probability they died was 0.25. Line 6 tells us for those women, if they had 1 or 2 siblings the probability they lived was 0.55. Next it tells us for those women if they were 7 years of age or older they had a 0.91 probability of surviving. The same line also tells us that those under the age of 7 had a 0.49 probability of dying. For those under the age of 7, if they had no siblings they had 0.35 probability of dying. For those with one of more siblings they had a 0.57 probability of surviving. For those women who had one or more sibling and survived, if they were younger than 28 they had a 0.33 probability of dying, if they were 28 or older they had a 0.63 probability of living.
